    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-08-28T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-08-28T15:00:00-05:00" n="322"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d322">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/1620: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Standley</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-08-28T23:00:00+03:00"
                            >August 28, 1943—11 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received August 29—12:50 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1216. Personal for the Secretary. Your 749, August 26, 7 p.m., my 1201, August
                    27, 5 p.m. The British Ambassador has received a note from Molotov dated August
                    27 which reads in paraphrased translation as follows: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>[“]The Soviet Government has acquainted itself with the Italian surrender
                            terms which have been approved by the American and British Governments
                            as transmitted by Ambassador Kerr and Ambassador Standley on August
                            26.</p>
                        <p>The Soviet Government approves the terms in question. It empowers General
                            Eisenhower to sign the terms in the negotiations with Castellano on
                            behalf of the Soviet Government.<note n="70" xml:id="d322fn70">For text
                                of Italian Armistice signed September 3, 1943, but not announced
                                until September 8, see Department of State, <hi rend="italic">United
                                    States and Italy, 1936–1946</hi>, Documentary Record
                                (Washington, Government Printing Office, 1946), p. 51, or Treaties
                                and Other International Acts Series No. 1604, or 61 Stat. (pt. 3)
                                2740.</note>
                        </p>
                        <p>In the present instance it is the opinion of the Soviet Government that a
                            special representative of the Soviet Union is not required when the
                            Italian terms of surrender are signed by General Eisenhower.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Standley</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
